WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.720
I'm David. I run R for the rest of us. I'm here to talk to you about starting a business

00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:17.240
with R. But here's the thing. I never actually intended to start my own business. And to

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:22.280
show you how unintentional my path to doing what I do now has been, let me give you a

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:29.799
brief story. In 2015, I was working my last 9 to 5 job. My wife had just started a job

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:34.119
at the time. It was a pretty challenging job, but she likes challenging jobs. At the

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:39.840
time, we were hoping to have kids, so we were overjoyed when we found out that she was pregnant

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:45.840
with not one but two kids. We were going to have twins. Now, at the time, we talked about

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:50.480
what to do. I really like kids. I used to be an elementary school teacher, so we decided

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:56.799
that I would stay home with our kids and she would continue working. Now, for those of

00:00:56.799 --> 00:01:02.279
you who have kids, you might not be surprised to hear that my pre-kid vision of what being

00:01:02.279 --> 00:01:07.860
a full-time stay-at-home dad would be like was pretty different from the post-kid reality.

00:01:07.860 --> 00:01:14.400
And so after a few months, my wife very kindly said to me, you know, it's okay if this isn't

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:19.839
going to quite work out the way we imagined it might. What happened, though, at the same

00:01:19.839 --> 00:01:24.400
time was that the challenging job that my wife, Rachel, had started actually came to

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:29.800
feel untenable. Having young kids and an incredibly challenging job was just a bit

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:35.239
too much. And she ended up leaving that job. So in a few months, we had gone from having

00:01:35.239 --> 00:01:42.360
two jobs and zero kids to having zero jobs and two kids. And it was at that time I realized,

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:46.680
okay, I need to do something to bring in a little income for our family. So I started

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:52.599
doing some freelance data analysis work. I was an Excel user at the time. I used Excel

00:01:52.599 --> 00:01:57.360
for everything. But I got a little bit bored. And I had heard about R. And I had heard that

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:02.320
R could, you know, do some nice stuff, automate things, make nice data viz. And I was like,

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:08.119
okay, cool, let me learn that. I taught myself R. And in the process realized, first of all,

00:02:08.119 --> 00:02:11.919
that I really liked it. And second of all, that there were a lot of people like me who

00:02:11.919 --> 00:02:18.360
also wanted to learn R. And so it was from that experience that I started R for the Rest

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:26.600
of Us. Today, R for the Rest of Us does both education work, we have online courses, trainings

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:33.399
for organizations, as well as consulting work. And I'm going to use examples from our business.

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:41.080
But this isn't really ultimately a talk about my business. This is a talk about your business.

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:46.279
I'm going to focus mostly on marketing, on how to sell your work. And the reason why

00:02:46.279 --> 00:02:50.360
is it's the thing that people who are thinking about starting their own business ask me the

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:54.639
most. They say, David, I want to start my own business, but I have no idea how to find

00:02:54.639 --> 00:03:01.600
clients. How did you do it? And I know there are some people potentially in the room, maybe

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:04.199
you're waiting for the next talk, who are thinking, you know what, I don't actually

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:08.759
want to start my own business. Before you run for the doors, I think the reason you

00:03:08.759 --> 00:03:14.240
might consider staying is that marketing matters, even if you're just working, if even if you

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:18.399
aren't working for someone else. So you need to, for example, sell your own work within

00:03:18.399 --> 00:03:22.919
your own organization. So your boss or your co-workers see what you're capable of, maybe

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:26.639
you're making an R package, and you want to get it out into the world, you need to market

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:33.000
it. So rather than put our heads in the sand and not do any marketing, let's learn how

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:41.000
to do marketing well. A quick question, if you would say that you like marketing, would

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:53.720
you go ahead and raise your hand? So I see a handful, maybe like 10 max. Not that many

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.639
people in the room, I would say overall, say they enjoy marketing. And I think the reason

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:05.440
why is this. Technical people like us tend to be pretty allergic to marketing. And I

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:10.600
know that because I, in the past, very much felt like this. We think, okay, if I write

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:16.559
really good code, that should be enough. I shouldn't have to go out and sell it, right?

00:04:16.559 --> 00:04:21.640
What I've realized is that what, another thing I've come to realize in the last few years

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:26.540
is that when people say that they don't like marketing, the marketing they're thinking

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:30.920
of is often kind of like this, right? Like think about stuff you've seen on social media

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:36.679
with a ton of hashtags linked to who knows where, trying to sell who knows what, right?

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.119
That type of like sleazy marketing. But what I've come to realize in running R for the

00:04:41.119 --> 00:04:46.320
rest of us is that marketing can actually look more like this, can look like education,

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:50.600
it can look like teaching. And so I think when you do marketing well, it doesn't actually

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:56.640
even necessarily seem like marketing. Let me give some examples from other people who

00:04:56.640 --> 00:05:03.239
run kind of consulting businesses of how they talk about marketing and ways that their approach

00:05:03.239 --> 00:05:10.160
also shows up in what we do with R for the rest of us. So Paul Miners was asked how he

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:15.040
does marketing, how he finds his clients. He's a consultant who trains on like Asana

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:19.559
and Pipe Drive. The details don't really matter, but what he said is, the way I do marketing

00:05:19.559 --> 00:05:26.559
is simple. I go to where my ideal clients are and I'm helpful. And so with R for the

00:05:27.359 --> 00:05:33.079
rest of us, what that's meant is we go to where people are, which probably won't be

00:05:33.079 --> 00:05:37.720
a huge surprise for folks here, is Twitter. That's where the R community tends to show

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:42.440
up. And the way we're helpful is every day for the last three and a half years, we have

00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:49.440
tweeted out one tip every day at 7.30 a.m. Sometimes things that we create, oftentimes

00:05:50.119 --> 00:05:55.959
things that other people create. And so through doing that, we've been able to build up a

00:05:55.959 --> 00:06:02.959
following of over 15,000 followers, which becomes useful in ways I'll talk about shortly.

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:10.119
Wes Boss talks about his approach being this. Share your knowledge for free with no strings

00:06:10.119 --> 00:06:17.119
attached. On the R for the rest of us website, we have a blog. There are a bunch of posts.

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:24.320
This is an example of one on how to set up Git and GitHub if you're working with R. And

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:27.440
I wrote it, first of all, because it was something I struggled with, so I figured other people

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:32.320
probably would as well. People can go on the R for the rest of us website, can read this

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:39.160
for free. They don't have to pay us anything. And I'm totally fine with that. I want to

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:46.160
give that value. And the thing with offering things for free is that this is taken from

00:06:47.320 --> 00:06:53.000
Adam Latham, who says that giving away your work for free is like compressing a spring

00:06:53.399 --> 00:07:00.040
and that spring releases when you finally have something up for sale. So rather than

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:03.480
thinking about marketing as going out and saying, hey, I'm selling this, I'm selling

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:09.559
that, it's much better if you can go out and offer value, offer things for free, and once

00:07:09.559 --> 00:07:14.079
you get that goodwill, hopefully get some following as well, then you can offer things

00:07:14.079 --> 00:07:19.959
that are paid. So this is an email that I send out twice a year announcing the start

00:07:19.959 --> 00:07:26.959
of a program called R in Three Months, where we do a three-month training program for folks.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:31.320
And when I send that out, because we've built up that goodwill, because we've offered things

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:38.119
for free, people are more interested in signing up. I'm going to now offer kind of four lessons

00:07:38.119 --> 00:07:44.640
that have been really useful for me in thinking about how to find clients. So if we think

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:49.920
about, okay, marketing done well generally looks like kind of education, what are some

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:56.920
more specific ways that we can look for clients? So the first lesson that I'm going to offer

00:07:58.119 --> 00:08:05.119
is to think about going deep, not broad. So people will sometimes say to me, hey, I really

00:08:07.399 --> 00:08:12.959
like what you're doing, you know, I like teaching too, like I'd love to start a business training

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.959
people to learn R. And they'll say, and I'll ask, you know, okay, great, like who are you

00:08:17.959 --> 00:08:24.119
thinking about trying to work with? And I'll say, well, anybody. But here's the problem.

00:08:24.119 --> 00:08:31.119
If you try to speak to everyone, no one will listen. Your message is just too general,

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:36.919
and people don't, it's not going to resonate if it's overly general. So instead, what you

00:08:36.919 --> 00:08:42.359
really want to do is find your people. In business speak, people will talk about niching

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:49.400
down, finding a niche that you can work in. And so with R for the rest of us, even the

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:56.400
name of the business, that was like my first attempt to kind of niche down. I'm not necessarily

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:02.760
trying to train everybody, I'm training the rest of us. Now, of course, everybody interprets

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:07.400
that slightly differently, but generally speaking, what I think of as our kind of ideal audience

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:14.200
is people who want to learn R, but are intimidated by it. And I pitch everything to that specific

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:21.200
audience. On marketing emails that go out, in the footer of those emails, this is what

00:09:22.280 --> 00:09:26.799
the text says. Think you know what an R user looks like? I'm probably not what you have

00:09:26.799 --> 00:09:32.880
in mind. Not a hardcore quant. I won't jump on you for any small mistake. And I want to

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:39.640
help others avoid the pain. And you can see through this language, I am trying to identify

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:44.280
this is the type of person that I think R for the rest of us is best for. It's not that

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:49.159
other people couldn't. I think anybody can learn R through the materials that we offer.

00:09:49.159 --> 00:09:53.359
But this is really like our ideal audience. And so with some people, that's not going

00:09:53.359 --> 00:09:57.280
to resonate, and that's okay. But for other people, that really will resonate, and they'll

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:03.840
be inclined to learn R through us, whereas a more general framing probably wouldn't appeal

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:10.840
to them. In addition to turning people on, having language that speaks to certain people,

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:15.679
it's really important also to turn people off. And I know that sounds counterintuitive,

00:10:15.679 --> 00:10:19.479
because you think, well, you want to have an offering that's going to be, you know,

00:10:19.479 --> 00:10:24.479
like applicable to anybody. But it actually doesn't work very well. And turning people

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:29.239
off is a really effective strategy to help you identify the niche that you do want to

00:10:29.239 --> 00:10:36.239
work in. So I'm in the process of writing a book. It's called R Without Statistics,

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:43.200
which is my attempt to both say what the book is, but also what it's not. It's broadly speaking

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:48.239
a book about kind of quirky, interesting things that you can do with R that don't involve

00:10:48.239 --> 00:10:55.239
any complex statistics. So when I tweeted about this in March, I got this feedback.

00:10:55.280 --> 00:11:00.119
Luis wrote, marketing tip, the label will create a huge barrier among statisticians

00:11:00.119 --> 00:11:05.960
and scholars. And I put this up not in any way to disparage Luis. Like, I really appreciate

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:11.840
the feedback. But the thing is, that's not my target audience. Statisticians and scholars

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:15.679
are, I mean, maybe they'll read the book. I'm more than happy for them to read the book.

00:11:15.679 --> 00:11:20.080
But that's not the audience that I'm going for. And by calling it R Without Statistics,

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:27.080
I'm intentionally trying to turn some people on, but also turn some people off.

00:11:27.799 --> 00:11:34.400
Lesson two, focus on results. So it's really easy for those of us who are technical to

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:38.919
get really into the tools that we use. You know, we want to talk about this new package

00:11:38.919 --> 00:11:43.820
or this new function that I learned. For clients, though, what they really care about is getting

00:11:43.820 --> 00:11:50.820
to the goal. As an example of this, two or three years ago, a potential client came to

00:11:50.979 --> 00:11:56.500
us from the state of Connecticut. And they said, David, we have to produce 169 reports,

00:11:56.500 --> 00:12:01.700
one for each town in the state of Connecticut. We use Excel. We have no idea how this is

00:12:01.700 --> 00:12:04.260
going to work. I've heard that R can maybe do this.

00:12:04.260 --> 00:12:08.020
In my head, what I'm thinking is, yeah, of course, like R Markdown parameterized reporting

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:12.299
and page down package. But that's not at all what I'm going to say to them. Instead, I'm

00:12:12.299 --> 00:12:16.440
going to frame it as, yeah, we can help you to automate this. We can do it more efficiently.

00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:21.700
And we'll also do it in a way that there will be fewer copy-paste errors. They care about

00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:27.020
that end result. They don't care about the tools generally that we're using.

00:12:27.020 --> 00:12:32.859
So we did that report, and this is what we ended up producing entirely with the tools

00:12:32.859 --> 00:12:36.780
that I talked about. On the R for the rest of us website, on the

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:43.659
consulting page, the headline is Communicate More Effectively and Efficiently. Note that

00:12:43.659 --> 00:12:49.619
I'm not talking about any R packages, anything like that. I'm talking about how to communicate

00:12:49.619 --> 00:12:53.380
effectively and efficiently, which is language that I think will resonate with my clients

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:58.299
and potential clients. Lesson three is to make your client the hero.

00:12:58.299 --> 00:13:03.419
It's really easy when you're developing marketing materials early on to say, I can do this,

00:13:03.419 --> 00:13:08.739
I can do that. But really, the way you want to position yourself is as the guide that

00:13:08.739 --> 00:13:15.260
is helping your client, but the client remains the hero of the story.

00:13:15.260 --> 00:13:23.659
So this is a report we did in 2020, maybe 2021, on census outreach efforts in the 2020

00:13:23.659 --> 00:13:28.380
census. And when I write about this, I have a case study on the R for the rest of us website.

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:34.539
Here's what I say. The 52 reports helped Oris Impact and the Democracy Funders Network,

00:13:34.539 --> 00:13:40.940
that was our client, to achieve their goals and more. And they did this without the agonizing

00:13:40.940 --> 00:13:45.299
manual work. So I'm talking about, I'm framing it in a way that I think will resonate with

00:13:45.299 --> 00:13:52.619
potential new clients, and I'm framing the client here as the hero, not saying, you know,

00:13:52.619 --> 00:13:56.780
we did this. I'm saying we helped them to make these reports without that agonizing

00:13:56.780 --> 00:14:04.179
manual work. Last lesson is this. Relationships matter more than technical skills. When you're

00:14:04.179 --> 00:14:08.380
starting out, it's really easy to think, you know, I just got to, like, tweak this one

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:12.700
bit of CSS on my website. To be honest, that doesn't really matter that much when you first

00:14:12.700 --> 00:14:16.299
start out, because your first clients are almost certainly going to come from people

00:14:16.299 --> 00:14:21.179
you know. At the same time that you cultivate existing relationships, it's important to

00:14:21.179 --> 00:14:26.059
cultivate new relationships. So for me, what this often looks like is I'll see people tweet

00:14:26.059 --> 00:14:30.539
about art for the rest of us. And I'm really grateful when they do. Of course, it's like

00:14:30.539 --> 00:14:34.260
fantastic marketing for me. So I'll follow up with them, and I'll say, you know, thank

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:38.140
you for doing that. I really appreciate that. And I'll do something like give them a free

00:14:38.140 --> 00:14:44.059
course. And so by doing that, you know, I make, hopefully, cultivate a good relationship,

00:14:44.059 --> 00:14:48.659
but then also maybe this person signs up for another course or are in three months or mentions

00:14:48.659 --> 00:14:54.460
it to a colleague. I think it can lead to other things in the future. So to wrap up,

00:14:54.460 --> 00:15:03.140
I want to leave you with this idea. You are not me. I've given examples here, and I've

00:15:03.140 --> 00:15:09.700
drawn lessons from the work of art for the rest of us. But it's really important to focus

00:15:09.700 --> 00:15:15.020
not so much on the specific tactics that we've used, rather focusing on the larger lessons.

00:15:15.020 --> 00:15:18.700
As an example, if you were thinking about becoming a consultant working with data science

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:24.619
teams, you'd probably talk more about the technical side of things than we tend to.

00:15:24.619 --> 00:15:29.219
But you still want to do it in a way that frames the conversation around the end result

00:15:29.219 --> 00:15:36.700
as opposed to an overemphasis on the technical tools themselves. So I hope I have left you

00:15:36.700 --> 00:15:43.700
with the idea that it is possible to sell your work without selling your soul.

